<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<theorem xmlns="Theorem"
         xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
         type="Corollary"
         id="Thm_ChangeCoordinatesMatrixInverse"
         xsi:schemaLocation="Theorem file:/C:/xampp/htdocs/moodle/mod/msm/NewSchemas/Theorem.xsd">
   <caption>Reversing coordinate change</caption>
   <associate type="Example">
      <showme.pack.ref showmePackID="Exa_ChangeCoordinatesReversal"/>
      <info>
         <para>
            <para.body>An example of reversing coordinate inversion.</para.body>
         </para>
      </info>
   </associate>
   <statement.theorem>
      <para>
         <para.body>If <math>
               <latex>\EuScript{B}</latex>
            </math> and <math>
               <latex>\EuScript{C}</latex>
            </math> are ordered bases of a subvector space <math>
               <latex>W</latex>
            </math> of <math>
               <latex>\RNr[n]</latex>
            </math>, then
			</para.body>
         <index.glossary>
            <term>change of coordinates matrix</term>
            <term>reversal of coordinate change</term>
            <info>
               <math.array column="3">
                  <row rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <text>=</text>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>\left(\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}}\right)^{-1}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
            </info>
         </index.glossary>
      </para>
      <math.array column="3">
         <row rowspan="1">
            <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
               <math>
                  <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}}</latex>
               </math>
            </cell>
            <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
               <text>=</text>
            </cell>
            <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
               <math>
                  <latex>\left(\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}}\right)^{-1}</latex>
               </math>
            </cell>
         </row>
      </math.array>
   </statement.theorem>
   <proof type="Proof">
      <proof.block>
         <proof.block.body>
            <para>
               <para.body>For an arbitrary vector <math>
                     <latex>\Vect{x}</latex>
                  </math> in <math>
                     <latex>W</latex>
                  </math> we find</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}} = \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}} \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}} \Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}} \quad\text{and}\quad \Vect{x}_{\EuScript{C}} = \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}} \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}} \Vect{x}_{\EuScript{C}}</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>Now, if <math>
                     <latex>\dim(W)=r</latex>
                  </math>, we also have that</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>\Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}} = \IdMtrx[r] \Vect{x}_{\EuScript{B}} \quad\text{and}\quad \Vect{x}_{\EuScript{C}} = \IdMtrx[r] \Vect{x}_{\EuScript{C}}</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>As coordinate conversion matrices are unique, this gives</para.body>
            </para>
            <math.display>
               <latex>\Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}} \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}} = \IdMtrx[n] \quad\text{and}\quad \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{C}\EuScript{B}} \Mtrx{C}_{\EuScript{B}\EuScript{C}} = \IdMtrx[n]</latex>
            </math.display>
            <para>
               <para.body>This implies the corollary on reversing coordinate conversion.</para.body>
            </para>
         </proof.block.body>
      </proof.block>
   </proof>
</theorem>
